definition.value: Catalysis of the reaction -  acyl-CoA + NADP+ -eq- trans-2,3-dehydroacyl-CoA + NADPH + H+.
Catalysis of the reaction -  2-octaprenylphenol + NADPH + O2 + H+ -eq- 2-octaprenyl-6-hydroxyphenol + NADP+ + H2O.
Catalysis of the reaction -  (R)-lactaldehyde + NAD+ -eq- methylglyoxal + NADH + H+.
Catalysis of the reaction -  a (3R)-3-hydroxyacyl-[acyl-carrier protein] -eq- H2O + a trans-delta2-enoyl-acyl-[acyl-carrier protein].
Catalysis of the reaction -  methylglyoxal + H2O -eq- D-lactate.
Catalysis of the reaction -  tetrahydrothiophene 1-oxide + reduced acceptor -eq- tetrahydrothiophene + acceptor.
Catalysis of the reaction -  dihydroneopterin monophosphate -eq- dihydroneopterin + phosphate.
Catalysis of the reaction -  dihydroneopterin triphosphate -eq- dihydroneopterin phosphate + diphosphate.
Catalysis of the reaction -  H2O + NADP+ -eq- NAD+ + phosphate.
Catalysis of the reaction -  dTDP-4-amino-4,6-dideoxy-D-glucose + 2-oxoglutarate -eq- dTDP-4-dehydro-6-deoxy-D-glucose + L-glutamate.
Catalysis of the reaction -  2-oxoglutarate + dTDP-4-amino-4,6-dideoxy-D-galactose -eq- L-glutamate + dTDP-4-dehydro-6-deoxy-D-galactose.
Catalysis of the reaction -  a halohydrin -eq- an epoxide + a hydrogen halide.
Catalysis of the transmembrane transfer of a chloride ion by a channel that opens when histamine has been bound by the channel complex or one of its constituent parts.
A protein complex that forms a transmembrane channel through which chloride ions may pass in response to histamine binding to the channel complex or one of its constituent parts.
A protein complex that recognizes the proximal sequence element of RNA polymerase II and III snRNA promoters.
Catalysis of the transfer of an acyl group from acyl-CoA to a nitrogen atom on an acceptor molecule.
Catalysis of the transfer of a mannose residue to an oligosaccharide, forming a beta-(1--gt-4) linkage.

Catalysis of the transfer of cellobiose from one side of the membrane to the other. Cellobiose, or 4-O-beta-D-glucopyranosyl-D-glucose, is a disaccharide that represents the basic repeating unit of cellulose.

Catalysis of the transfer of sorbose from one side of the membrane to the other. Sorbose is the ketohexose xylo-2-hexulose -  L-sorbose is formed by bacterial oxidation of sorbitol. Sorbose is produced commercially by fermentation and is used as an intermediate in the manufacture of ascorbic acid.

Catalysis of the transfer of galactosamine from one side of the membrane to the other. Galactosamine is an aminodeoxysugar -  D-galactosamine is a constituent of some glycolipids and glycosaminoglycans, commonly as its N-acetyl derivative.
Includes phosphoenolpyruvate-protein phosphatase (enzyme I of the phosphotransferase system) and protein-N(PI)-phosphohistidine-sugar phosphotransferase (enzyme II of the phosphotransferase system).

Combining with a signal and transmitting the signal from one side of the membrane to the other to initiate a change in cell activity by catalysis of the reaction -  a phosphoprotein + H2O -eq- a protein + phosphate.

Combining with a signal and transmitting the signal from one side of the membrane to the other to initiate a change in cell activity by catalysis of the reaction -  a protein + ATP -eq- a phosphoprotein + ADP.
Catalysis of the transfer of a phosphate group, usually from ATP, to a carbohydrate substrate molecule.
Catalysis of the reaction -  ATP + nucleoside monophosphate -eq- ADP + nucleoside diphosphate.
Catalysis of the transfer of a phosphate group, usually from ATP, to an amino acid substrate.
Catalysis of the reaction -  carbohydrate phosphate + H2O -eq- carbohydrate + phosphate.
Catalysis of the transfer of a phosphate group, usually from ATP or GTP, to a nucleobase, nucleoside, nucleotide or polynucleotide substrate.
Catalysis of the reaction -  ATP + nucleoside -eq- ADP + nucleoside monophosphate.
Modulates the activity of a kinase, an enzyme which catalyzes of the transfer of a phosphate group, usually from ATP, to a substrate molecule.
Modulates the activity of a phosphatase, an enzyme which catalyzes of the removal of a phosphate group from a substrate molecule.
Increases the activity of a kinase, an enzyme which catalyzes of the transfer of a phosphate group, usually from ATP, to a substrate molecule.
Stops, prevents or reduces the activity of a kinase, an enzyme which catalyzes of the transfer of a phosphate group, usually from ATP, to a substrate molecule.
Increases the activity of a phosphatase, an enzyme which catalyzes of the removal of a phosphate group from a substrate molecule.
Stops, prevents or reduces the activity of a phosphatase, an enzyme which catalyzes of the removal of a phosphate group from a substrate molecule.
Catalysis of the hydrolysis of an acetyl group or groups from a substrate molecule.

Interacting selectively and non-covalently with an intermediate filament, a distinct elongated structure, characteristically 10 nm in diameter, that occurs in the cytoplasm of higher eukaryotic cells. Intermediate filaments form a fibrous system, composed of chemically heterogeneous subunits and involved in mechanically integrating the various components of the cytoplasmic space.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a centromere, a region of chromosome where the spindle fibers attach during mitosis and meiosis.
Catalysis of the hydrolysis of any non-peptide carbon-nitrogen bond in a cyclic amidine, a compound of the form R-C(-eq-NH)-NH2, in a reaction that involves the opening of a ring.
Catalysis of the removal of an amino group from a substrate, producing ammonia (NH3).
Catalysis of the transfer of oxalate from one side of the membrane to the other. Oxalate, or ethanedioic acid, occurs in many plants and is highly toxic to animals.

Enables the directed movement of a toxin into, out of or within a cell, or between cells. A toxin is a poisonous compound (typically a protein) that is produced by cells or organisms and that can cause disease when introduced into the body or tissues of an organism.
Catalysis of the transfer of ferric-vibriobactin ions from one side of a membrane to the other.
Catalysis of the transfer of a methyl group from S-adenosyl-L-methionine to the delta-nitrogen atom of peptidyl-arginine residues.
Catalysis of the transfer of a myristoyl group to a sulfur atom on a cysteine residue of a protein molecule.
Catalysis of the transfer of a palmitoyl group to a sulfur atom on the cysteine of a protein molecule.
Catalysis of the transfer of an acyl group to a sulfur atom on the cysteine of a protein molecule.
Catalysis of the reaction -  (R)-mevalonate + NADP(+) -eq- H(+) + mevaldate + NADPH.
Catalysis of the reaction -  (R)-mevalonate + NAD(+) -eq- H(+) + mevaldate + NADH.
Combining with the Fc region of an immunoglobulin protein and transmitting the signal from one side of the membrane to the other to initiate a change in cell activity.
